revision.text:
'''Tōkan-yama Kofun''' (とうかんやま古墳) is a {{ill|Zenpokoenfun|lt=Zenpō-kōen-fun (keyhole-shaped tumulus)|en|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Minowa, Kumagaya|ja|箕輪|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kumagaya|ja|熊谷市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Saitama Prefecture|ja|埼玉県|12=draft|12=draft}}, Japan. It is designated as a Saitama Prefecture Historic Site.
== Overview == The Tōkan-yama Kofun is situated in central Hiki Plateau in central Saitama Prefecture. The tumulus gets its name from the Inari Shrine (referred to locally as "Otōka-sama") and the Tōkanya Monument located on the mound. While parts of the mound have been altered over time, no archaeological excavation has been conducted.
The kofun is keyhole-shaped, with its front portion facing southwest.<ref name="説明板">Historical Site Explanation Board.</ref> Measuring 75 meters in length, it is the largest kofun in Kumagaya City and comparable in size to the Kawarazuka Kofun in the {{ill|Sakitama Kofun Cluster|ja|埼玉古墳群|12=draft|12=draft}} located in Gyōda.<ref name="熊谷市デジタルミュージアム"/> Cylindrical {{ill|haniwa|en|埴輪|12=draft|12=draft}} fragments have been collected from the mound surface.<ref name="説明板"/> The mound is believed to have had a surrounding moat, although it is now buried.<ref name="熊谷市デジタルミュージアム"/> The burial facility remains undetermined but is presumed to be a {{ill|Single-entry horizontal stone chamber|lt=Yokoana-shiki sekishitsu (horizontal stone chamber)|en|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="熊谷市デジタルミュージアム"/> The nature of grave goods is not well understood.
The Tōkan-yama Kofun is thought to have been constructed in the late {{ill|Kofun period|en|古墳時代|12=draft|12=draft}} (late 6th century),<ref name="熊谷市デジタルミュージアム">[http://www.kumagaya-bunkazai.jp/museum/jousetu/bunkazai/038bunka.htm Tōkan-yama Kofun] (Kumagaya Municipal Kōnan Cultural Heritage Center "Kumagaya Digital Museum").</ref><ref name="一覧"/> or possibly mid-6th century.<ref name="説明板"/> It is situated on the eastern edge of the large Mitsuhozuka Kofun Cluster at the northern end of the Hiki Plateau and, along with the {{ill|Kabutoyama Kofun (Kumagaya)|ja|甲山古墳 (熊谷市)|lt=Kabutoyama Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}} located about 1 kilometer to the north, is considered to indicate the presence of a significant regional leader connected to the Saitama Kofun Cluster.
The tumulus was designated a Saitama Prefecture Historic Site in 1989 (Heisei 1).<ref name="一覧"/>
== Kofun Details == The mound's dimensions are as follows:<ref name="熊谷市デジタルミュージアム"/> * Kofun length: 75 meters (alternatively 74 meters<ref name="説明板"/>) * Rear circular section: ** Diameter: 37 meters ** Height: 6.2 meters * Front square section: ** Length: 38 meters <gallery> File:Tokan-yama Kofun, kouenbu.jpg|View from the front section toward the rear File:Tokan-yama Kofun, zenpoubu.jpg|View from the rear section toward the front File:Tokan-yama Kofun, inari-jinja.jpg|Inari Shrine at the apex of the front section File:Tokan-yama Kofun, funkyu-2.jpg|Front section mound </gallery>
== Cultural Properties == === Saitama Prefecture Designated Cultural Properties === * Historic Site ** Tōkan-yama Kofun - Owned by Hoan-ji Temple. Designated on March 17, 1989.<ref name="一覧">{{PDFlink|[https://www.pref.saitama.lg.jp/documents/27121/22kensiseki.pdf Saitama Prefecture Historic Sites]}} (Saitama Prefecture Homepage).</ref>
